00:19:52.543 --> 00:19:54.460
Thanks.

00:19:54.460 --> 00:19:57.915
OK, so for the rest of today
and the rest of this week,

00:19:57.915 --> 00:20:00.040
we're going to talk about
a different kind of proof

00:20:00.040 --> 00:20:03.600
technique, which is induction.

00:20:03.600 --> 00:20:07.510
Now, induction is by far the
most powerful and commonly used

00:20:07.510 --> 00:20:10.350
proof technique in
computer science.

00:20:10.350 --> 00:20:11.880
If there's one thing
you should know

00:20:11.880 --> 00:20:14.640
by the time you're
done with this class,

00:20:14.640 --> 00:20:16.415
it's how to do a
proof by induction.

00:20:16.415 --> 00:20:17.790
In fact, if there's
one thing you

00:20:17.790 --> 00:20:20.280
will know by the time
we're done with this class,

00:20:20.280 --> 00:20:22.020
is how to do a
proof by induction.

00:20:22.020 --> 00:20:25.240
And in some sense, when we
get to grading the final, how

00:20:25.240 --> 00:20:27.020
we measure ourselves
as instructors,

00:20:27.020 --> 00:20:29.770
the first test is,
can you do the proof

00:20:29.770 --> 00:20:32.250
by induction question,
and do a good proof there?

00:20:32.250 --> 00:20:35.090
You will see it on the
midterm and the final,

00:20:35.090 --> 00:20:38.410
probably in multiple instances.

00:20:38.410 --> 00:20:40.960
Now just to make sure you
become intimately familiar

00:20:40.960 --> 00:20:44.480
with induction, we're going
to do over a dozen proofs

00:20:44.480 --> 00:20:46.720
with induction in class,
and many more in homework

00:20:46.720 --> 00:20:49.610
over the next five to six weeks.

00:20:49.610 --> 00:20:51.670
You'll probably be
dreaming about induction,

00:20:51.670 --> 00:20:53.940
if we're successful here.

00:20:53.940 --> 00:20:55.130
Soon.

00:20:55.130 --> 00:20:57.984
The good news is that
induction is very easy.

00:20:57.984 --> 00:21:00.150
Once you get your mind
around it, get some practice,

00:21:00.150 --> 00:21:02.910
it really is not a hard thing.

00:21:02.910 --> 00:21:05.600
In fact, induction is
really just an axiom.

00:21:08.290 --> 00:21:09.350
So let me state it.

00:21:16.950 --> 00:21:19.720
Let P(n) be a predicate.

00:21:26.740 --> 00:21:44.940
If P(0) is true, and for all
natural numbers n, p of n

00:21:44.940 --> 00:21:51.140
implies p of n plus 1 is true.

00:21:51.140 --> 00:21:53.850
So here I'm saying that
this is true for all n.

00:21:59.525 --> 00:22:00.025
OK.

00:22:02.620 --> 00:22:11.860
Then for all n, natural
numbers, P of n is true.

00:22:16.170 --> 00:22:18.220
I had another way of
saying this without the

00:22:18.220 --> 00:22:25.090
for alls there, is
that if P(0) is true,

00:22:25.090 --> 00:22:34.030
if P(0) implies P(1) is true,
if P(1) implies P(2) is true,

00:22:34.030 --> 00:22:40.240
and so on, forever, then p
of n is true for all that.

00:22:40.240 --> 00:22:48.990
So then, P(0), P(1),
P(2), forever, are true.

00:22:57.760 --> 00:22:59.900
OK.

00:22:59.900 --> 00:23:04.600
Now you can sort of see why
this is a reasonable axiom,

00:23:04.600 --> 00:23:10.440
because if P(0) is true,
and P(0) implies P(1), then

00:23:10.440 --> 00:23:13.640
by that modus ponens thing or
one of the logical deductions,

00:23:13.640 --> 00:23:16.000
we know P(1) is true.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:20.120
And if P(1) is true, and
P(1) implies P(2) is true,

00:23:20.120 --> 00:23:21.770
then we know by
the same reasoning,

00:23:21.770 --> 00:23:25.770
P(2) is true, and
so on, forever.

00:23:25.770 --> 00:23:28.870
Now the reason it becomes an
axiom is that and so on forever

00:23:28.870 --> 00:23:30.200
bit is part of it.

00:23:30.200 --> 00:23:33.370
That's why we need
it as an axiom.

00:23:33.370 --> 00:23:37.652
You could sort of view this
as a series of dominoes.

00:23:37.652 --> 00:23:57.300
You know, I got a
domino for each n,

00:23:57.300 --> 00:24:01.710
and each domino knocks over
the next in terms of truth,

00:24:01.710 --> 00:24:04.230
knocking over corresponds
to the truth here.

00:24:04.230 --> 00:24:08.400
And if I know P(0) is true,
that means I knock over P(0),

00:24:08.400 --> 00:24:11.210
P(0) implies P(1) means
P(1) one goes down.

00:24:11.210 --> 00:24:15.070
P(1) implies P(2) means P(2)
goes down, and so forth.

00:24:15.070 --> 00:24:16.230
Pretty basic.

00:24:19.035 --> 00:24:21.660
Raise your hand if you think you
don't have a lot of experience

00:24:21.660 --> 00:24:23.745
with induction.

00:24:23.745 --> 00:24:26.200
All right, yeah,
that's pretty typical.

00:24:26.200 --> 00:24:27.560
About a third to a half of you.

00:24:27.560 --> 00:24:30.640
So we're going to change that.

00:24:30.640 --> 00:24:32.390
Let's do a simple
proof using induction.

00:24:36.580 --> 00:24:40.600
So let's prove that for all
n bigger than or equal to 0,

00:24:40.600 --> 00:24:48.140
again natural numbers, that
1, plus 2, plus 3, plus n

00:24:48.140 --> 00:24:53.677
equals n times n plus 1 over 2.

00:24:53.677 --> 00:24:55.510
This is actually a
useful thing to remember.

00:24:55.510 --> 00:24:58.820
We're going to use this
all term, this identity.

00:24:58.820 --> 00:25:01.740
Now the first thing,
before we prove it,

00:25:01.740 --> 00:25:04.080
I want to make sure we
understand this dot,

00:25:04.080 --> 00:25:05.740
dot, dot, notation.

00:25:05.740 --> 00:25:08.690
Because it is the source
of a lot of errors.

00:25:08.690 --> 00:25:14.180
What it means is that you need
to fill in the pattern here,

00:25:14.180 --> 00:25:16.500
which is vague.

00:25:16.500 --> 00:25:19.380
What it means in this case,
you fill in four, five, six all

00:25:19.380 --> 00:25:21.865
the way up to n
minus 1, and then n.

00:25:21.865 --> 00:25:22.740
That's what it means.

00:25:22.740 --> 00:25:25.020
Figure out the pattern
and fill it in.

00:25:25.020 --> 00:25:27.340
Pretty risky thing.

00:25:27.340 --> 00:25:29.490
Now in this case,
because that's so vague,

00:25:29.490 --> 00:25:32.320
there's other terminology
we use for this.

00:25:32.320 --> 00:25:36.200
For example, we would
use a big sigma,

00:25:36.200 --> 00:25:40.250
capital sigma i
equals 0 to n of i.

00:25:40.250 --> 00:25:44.940
That means the sum of i,
where i is the integers from 0

00:25:44.940 --> 00:25:47.004
to n inclusive.

00:25:47.004 --> 00:25:48.170
Actually, let me put 1 here.

00:25:51.470 --> 00:25:54.830
Another way to write this--
these are all equivalent ways

00:25:54.830 --> 00:25:57.810
to write it-- is you
could put 1 less than

00:25:57.810 --> 00:26:01.005
or equal to i, less
than or equal to n of i.

00:26:01.005 --> 00:26:04.810
So you could put something i
over the range, from one to n,

00:26:04.810 --> 00:26:07.000
or you can write it on
the bottom if you want.

00:26:10.690 --> 00:26:12.730
So these are four
different ways of writing

00:26:12.730 --> 00:26:16.106
the same thing, the sum of the
natural numbers from 1 to n.

00:26:16.106 --> 00:26:17.730
And we'll use them
all during the term.

00:26:20.810 --> 00:26:22.750
All right, now there's
some special cases

00:26:22.750 --> 00:26:26.430
that make this a little
more interesting.

00:26:26.430 --> 00:26:27.686
What if n equals 1?

00:26:30.520 --> 00:26:35.570
I've got 1 plus 2 plus
dot, dot, dot, plus n.

00:26:38.490 --> 00:26:40.490
What do you suppose it
equals if n equals 1?

00:26:43.290 --> 00:26:48.910
1, because we're summing
the numbers from 1 to 1.

00:26:48.910 --> 00:26:51.390
That's just 1, the number 1.

00:26:51.390 --> 00:26:53.930
There is no 2.

00:26:53.930 --> 00:26:56.880
And there aren't
two copies of 1.

00:26:56.880 --> 00:26:58.910
So this notation
is very ambiguous.

00:26:58.910 --> 00:27:00.810
You'll see a 2 here in the sum.

00:27:00.810 --> 00:27:03.614
If n is 1, you'll see
a 1 here and a 1 here.

00:27:03.614 --> 00:27:04.780
So you've got to be careful.

00:27:04.780 --> 00:27:07.080
I guarantee you, you'll
make a mistake with this.

00:27:07.080 --> 00:27:09.371
In fact I'm going to show
you another false proof later

00:27:09.371 --> 00:27:11.244
where this comes into play.

00:27:11.244 --> 00:27:13.160
What about if n is less
than or equal to zero?

00:27:15.849 --> 00:27:16.515
What is it then?

00:27:20.950 --> 00:27:21.510
Any thoughts?

00:27:25.620 --> 00:27:26.680
0.

00:27:26.680 --> 00:27:32.889
There are no integers to sum,
no 1, no 2, no n, because you

00:27:32.889 --> 00:27:34.930
never get started because--
sorry, n is less than

00:27:34.930 --> 00:27:37.550
or equal to 0-- because
you're summing from 1 to 0,

00:27:37.550 --> 00:27:38.320
0 is below.

00:27:38.320 --> 00:27:40.710
You never-- it doesn't
include anything.

00:27:40.710 --> 00:27:45.120
So these are the conventions
to keep in mind with the edge

00:27:45.120 --> 00:27:45.710
cases here.

00:27:50.500 --> 00:27:53.300
All right, it's easy enough
to check that the theorem is

00:27:53.300 --> 00:27:54.640
true for certain values of n.

00:27:54.640 --> 00:28:00.520
For example, if n equals 4,
I've got 1 plus 2 plus 3 plus 4.

00:28:00.520 --> 00:28:02.220
That's 10.

00:28:02.220 --> 00:28:09.580
And 10 equals 4 times 5 over
2, plugging in the formula.

00:28:09.580 --> 00:28:13.030
So for any value of n you could
check this formula is true.

00:28:13.030 --> 00:28:15.930
Proving is true for all n.

00:28:15.930 --> 00:28:19.820
It takes a little more effort
unless you use induction.

00:28:19.820 --> 00:28:20.760
So let's do that.

00:28:23.430 --> 00:28:24.870
So we'll prove the theorem.

00:28:24.870 --> 00:28:27.200
Now, whenever you're using
a proof by induction,

00:28:27.200 --> 00:28:30.480
first thing you do is you
write down by induction

00:28:30.480 --> 00:28:33.920
so we know what
you're going to do.

00:28:33.920 --> 00:28:35.980
And the next thing
you need to do

00:28:35.980 --> 00:28:40.500
is figure out, what's
your predicate.

00:28:40.500 --> 00:28:43.060
What's your
inductive hypothesis?

00:28:43.060 --> 00:28:43.750
What's p?

00:28:46.310 --> 00:28:50.870
So usually p will
be the thing you're

00:28:50.870 --> 00:28:53.820
trying to prove, namely
that 1 plus 2 plus 3 up to n

00:28:53.820 --> 00:28:56.460
is n times n plus 1 over 2.

00:28:56.460 --> 00:28:57.390
And you state that.

00:28:57.390 --> 00:29:06.140
You say let p of n be the
proposition, the predicate,

00:29:06.140 --> 00:29:13.880
that the sum i equals 1
to n of i equals n times n

00:29:13.880 --> 00:29:14.897
plus 1 over 2.

00:29:17.669 --> 00:29:19.210
And once you've got
that established,

00:29:19.210 --> 00:29:24.300
now we're going to go
verify that p 0 is true

00:29:24.300 --> 00:29:29.030
and that p n implies p n plus 1.

00:29:29.030 --> 00:29:31.510
So we always have
to write this down.

00:29:31.510 --> 00:29:34.740
The next thing to do is to check
what's called the base case,

00:29:34.740 --> 00:29:36.165
p zero.

00:29:36.165 --> 00:29:37.300
So let's do that.

00:29:52.510 --> 00:29:54.130
So we write down base case.

00:29:54.130 --> 00:29:55.615
Some people call
it the basis step.

00:29:59.160 --> 00:30:03.060
And we have to check
that p 0 is true.

00:30:05.860 --> 00:30:13.650
Well, what's the sum of
i equals 1 to 0 of i?

00:30:13.650 --> 00:30:14.650
0.

00:30:14.650 --> 00:30:16.140
There are no terms in this sum.

00:30:18.750 --> 00:30:22.020
And if I look over there,
n times n plus 1 over 2.

00:30:22.020 --> 00:30:24.995
If n is 0, it equals 0.

00:30:28.346 --> 00:30:29.720
So we're done with
the base case.

00:30:29.720 --> 00:30:33.890
We've now proved
that p0 is true.

00:30:33.890 --> 00:30:36.935
And the second part is
called the inductive step.

00:30:42.460 --> 00:30:47.350
And here we have to show, for
n greater than or equal to 0,

00:30:47.350 --> 00:30:53.020
we need to show that pn
implies pn plus 1 is true.

00:31:01.620 --> 00:31:05.380
Now how do we show an
implication is true?

00:31:05.380 --> 00:31:06.580
How do I show this is true?

00:31:06.580 --> 00:31:09.810
What am I going to do to
show that's true in general?

00:31:09.810 --> 00:31:10.900
Yeah?

00:31:10.900 --> 00:31:11.775
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:31:19.060 --> 00:31:19.780
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:31:19.780 --> 00:31:24.230
Because an implication is true
in every case, except for true

00:31:24.230 --> 00:31:26.060
implies false.

00:31:26.060 --> 00:31:27.960
So if pn is false, we're done.

00:31:27.960 --> 00:31:29.410
This implication is true.

00:31:29.410 --> 00:31:32.530
The only case we have to
worry about is p of n is true.

00:31:32.530 --> 00:31:34.600
So we assume p of n is true.

00:31:34.600 --> 00:31:37.500
And now we confirm that that
means pn plus 1 is true.

00:31:40.920 --> 00:31:43.960
So we write that down.

00:31:43.960 --> 00:31:49.960
Assume pn is true.

00:31:49.960 --> 00:31:53.765
And you might also write down,
"for purposes of induction"

00:31:53.765 --> 00:31:59.490
or "purposes of it verifying
the inductive hypothesis." just

00:31:59.490 --> 00:32:01.152
to let us know why
you're assuming it.

00:32:01.152 --> 00:32:02.610
In other words,
you're not assuming

00:32:02.610 --> 00:32:05.615
pn is true for purposes
of contradiction.

00:32:05.615 --> 00:32:07.490
You're assuming it for
purposes of induction.

00:32:10.329 --> 00:32:11.370
All right, let's do that.

00:32:23.150 --> 00:32:27.400
That means, in this case, i.e.

00:32:27.400 --> 00:32:40.270
we assume 1 plus 2 plus up to n
equals n times n plus 1 over 2.

00:32:40.270 --> 00:32:49.910
And we need to show that
the n plus 1 case is true,

00:32:49.910 --> 00:32:58.350
and the 1 plus 2 plus n plus
1 equals n plus 1 times n

00:32:58.350 --> 00:33:00.960
plus 2 over 2.

00:33:04.710 --> 00:33:06.930
It's sort of weird,
and this does

00:33:06.930 --> 00:33:10.830
confuse people that aren't
familiar yet with induction.

00:33:10.830 --> 00:33:14.360
It looks like we just assumed
what we're trying to prove.

00:33:14.360 --> 00:33:16.410
We're trying to prove
this is true for all n.

00:33:16.410 --> 00:33:18.280
And we just assumed it.

00:33:18.280 --> 00:33:22.360
But we're assuming it in
the context of establishing

00:33:22.360 --> 00:33:24.080
this implication is true.

00:33:24.080 --> 00:33:26.730
And then we apply the
induction axiom to conclude pn

00:33:26.730 --> 00:33:27.480
is true for all n.

00:33:30.540 --> 00:33:39.040
All right, well, let's
rewrite this as 1 plus 2

00:33:39.040 --> 00:33:42.540
plus n plus n plus 1.

00:33:46.140 --> 00:33:50.130
Because I've assumed
pn, I can rewrite this

00:33:50.130 --> 00:33:54.960
as an n plus 1 over 2.

00:33:54.960 --> 00:33:59.600
And now plus n plus 1 out here.

00:33:59.600 --> 00:34:06.520
That equals, well, I got
n squared plus n, here,

00:34:06.520 --> 00:34:10.544
over 2, plus 2 n plus 2.

00:34:15.290 --> 00:34:22.050
And that equals n plus
one times n plus 2 over 2,

00:34:22.050 --> 00:34:25.830
which is what we're
trying to show.

00:34:25.830 --> 00:34:28.350
So we've completed,
now, the inductive step.

00:34:28.350 --> 00:34:33.976
We have shown that for all n,
pn implies pn plus one for all n

00:34:33.976 --> 00:34:35.100
greater than or equal to 0.

00:34:41.710 --> 00:34:45.760
Any questions about that?

00:34:45.760 --> 00:34:49.370
So, the proof is done.

00:34:49.370 --> 00:34:51.830
We've done everything we
need to imply induction.

00:34:51.830 --> 00:34:53.909
We've got p0 is true.

00:34:53.909 --> 00:34:56.820
And pn implies pn plus 1 for n
bigger than or equal to zero.

00:34:59.650 --> 00:35:05.138
Now induction helped
us prove the theorem.

00:35:05.138 --> 00:35:07.221
Did it help us understand
why the theorem is true?

00:35:09.879 --> 00:35:11.670
Do you have any feel
for why the theorem is

00:35:11.670 --> 00:35:12.836
true after seeing the proof?

00:35:15.410 --> 00:35:17.670
Not really.

00:35:17.670 --> 00:35:19.709
I don't think--
sometimes induction

00:35:19.709 --> 00:35:21.000
will give you an understanding.

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:21.900
Sometimes it won't.

00:35:21.900 --> 00:35:24.950
Here you've got no understanding
of why the theorem's true,

00:35:24.950 --> 00:35:27.160
which is sort of unfortunate.

00:35:27.160 --> 00:35:32.979
Did induction help you figure
out the answer to the sum?

00:35:32.979 --> 00:35:34.520
Namely, say you were
trying to derive

00:35:34.520 --> 00:35:35.810
this answer from this sum.

00:35:35.810 --> 00:35:39.730
Did induction give
you the answer?

00:35:39.730 --> 00:35:40.450
No.

00:35:40.450 --> 00:35:44.720
You had to know the answer,
namely this, in order

00:35:44.720 --> 00:35:47.320
to prove it was true.

00:35:47.320 --> 00:35:49.830
Now later we'll see examples
where induction actually

00:35:49.830 --> 00:35:52.380
can give you the answer,
but often it does not.

00:35:52.380 --> 00:35:55.280
Often, induction gives
you no hints, no answer,

00:35:55.280 --> 00:35:59.090
just prove that it's right once
you had the clever idea that,

00:35:59.090 --> 00:36:01.940
oh, maybe that's the answer.

00:36:01.940 --> 00:36:06.080
You'll see that with things
like the beaver flu problem.

00:36:06.080 --> 00:36:10.040
Figuring out the inductive
hypothesis or the answer,

00:36:10.040 --> 00:36:12.040
you know, the details
of it is hard.

00:36:12.040 --> 00:36:14.840
But once you do it, then
applying the induction,

00:36:14.840 --> 00:36:15.410
not so hard.

00:36:15.410 --> 00:36:16.660
It gives you a concrete proof.

00:36:19.309 --> 00:36:20.350
OK, let's do another one.

00:36:25.684 --> 00:36:27.850
In fact, we're just going
to spend the rest of today

00:36:27.850 --> 00:36:29.110
doing induction proofs.

00:36:35.380 --> 00:36:48.780
So for all natural numbers
n, 3 divides n cubed minus n.

00:36:48.780 --> 00:36:51.740
Means than n cubed minus
n is a multiple of three.

00:36:51.740 --> 00:36:53.940
For example, n is 5.

00:36:58.220 --> 00:37:06.720
3 divides 125 minus
5, because that's 120.

00:37:06.720 --> 00:37:09.191
Let's prove that.

00:37:09.191 --> 00:37:10.565
And we're going
to use induction.

00:37:17.620 --> 00:37:19.220
What do you suppose
pn's going to be?

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:26.810
What's my predicate or my
inductive hypothesis here?

00:37:26.810 --> 00:37:27.480
Any thoughts?

00:37:30.390 --> 00:37:31.752
Yeah?

00:37:31.752 --> 00:37:32.684
PROFESSOR: [INAUDIBLE]

00:37:32.684 --> 00:37:33.850
PROFESSOR: Yeah, that's you.

00:37:33.850 --> 00:37:34.638
Go ahead.

00:37:34.638 --> 00:37:36.224
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:37:36.224 --> 00:37:36.890
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:37:36.890 --> 00:37:38.710
First thing you
always want to try

00:37:38.710 --> 00:37:42.460
is you assume that is
your induction hypothesis.

00:37:42.460 --> 00:37:50.320
So we say, let pn be 3
divides n cubed minus n.

00:37:53.040 --> 00:37:56.230
What's the next thing
we do in our proof?

00:37:56.230 --> 00:37:56.830
Base case.

00:37:59.540 --> 00:38:03.200
Always easy to forget,
but not a good idea.

00:38:03.200 --> 00:38:05.550
Base case is n equals 0.

00:38:05.550 --> 00:38:09.850
And sure enough, 3
divides 0 minus 0.

00:38:09.850 --> 00:38:10.753
So that's done.

00:38:18.650 --> 00:38:20.210
What's the next step we do?

00:38:24.090 --> 00:38:24.590
What is it?

00:38:24.590 --> 00:38:25.270
Next step?

00:38:28.710 --> 00:38:29.810
Inductive step.

00:38:36.940 --> 00:38:41.960
And for that we're going to
need to show for n bigger

00:38:41.960 --> 00:38:49.661
than or equal to 0, we want
to show pn implies pn plus 1

00:38:49.661 --> 00:38:50.160
is true.

00:38:54.880 --> 00:38:57.130
So to do that we
assume pn is true.

00:39:04.750 --> 00:39:11.590
In other words, we assume that
3 divides n cubed minus n.

00:39:11.590 --> 00:39:15.690
And we're trying to show that
3 divides n plus 1 cubed minus

00:39:15.690 --> 00:39:17.270
n plus 1.

00:39:17.270 --> 00:39:25.050
So we take a look at, we examine
n plus 1 cubed minus n plus 1.

00:39:25.050 --> 00:39:29.070
And we want to show it's
a multiple of three.

00:39:29.070 --> 00:39:32.540
Well, let's expand that out.

00:39:32.540 --> 00:39:39.160
This is n cubed plus 3n
squared, plus 3n plus 1.

00:39:39.160 --> 00:39:44.100
And I subtract off n plus 1.

00:39:44.100 --> 00:39:48.846
So I get n cubed plus
3n squared plus 2n.

00:39:54.830 --> 00:39:55.985
Is this a multiple of 3?

00:39:59.600 --> 00:40:04.220
I need to show that's a multiple
of 3 and then I'd be all done.

00:40:04.220 --> 00:40:05.180
Is it a multiple of 3?

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:09.950
Beats me.

00:40:09.950 --> 00:40:12.965
It doesn't look like a
multiple of 3, necessarily.

00:40:16.350 --> 00:40:19.200
So maybe we need to
massage it a little bit.

00:40:19.200 --> 00:40:21.890
I do know that this
is a multiple of 3.

00:40:21.890 --> 00:40:23.579
I can use that fact.

00:40:23.579 --> 00:40:25.120
And in proofs by
induction you always

00:40:25.120 --> 00:40:27.290
want to-- if you're not
making use of that fact,

00:40:27.290 --> 00:40:29.390
then you're not really
making use of induction.

00:40:29.390 --> 00:40:30.390
Sort of a warning sign.

00:40:30.390 --> 00:40:34.220
So I want to use this
fact to prove this.

00:40:34.220 --> 00:40:39.520
Well, let's get a
minus n in here.

00:40:39.520 --> 00:40:44.700
This equals n cubed minus
n plus 3n squared plus--

00:40:44.700 --> 00:40:49.070
if I subtracted an n I
got to add an n-- plus 3n.

00:40:49.070 --> 00:40:50.700
So I've rewritten it.

00:40:50.700 --> 00:40:53.160
Now is it clear?

00:40:53.160 --> 00:40:54.740
Now it's clear.

00:40:54.740 --> 00:40:58.390
Very simple, because
3 divide this by pn.

00:40:58.390 --> 00:40:59.330
3 divides that.

00:40:59.330 --> 00:41:00.810
And 3 divides that.

00:41:00.810 --> 00:41:05.050
So this is a multiple
of 3, because I've

00:41:05.050 --> 00:41:12.150
got 3 divides 3n squared, 3
divides 3n, and 3 divides n

00:41:12.150 --> 00:41:17.120
cubed minus n by pn.

00:41:17.120 --> 00:41:20.640
Or you could say, by the
inductive hypothesis.

00:41:20.640 --> 00:41:25.680
pn is the inductive hypothesis,
another name for it.

00:41:25.680 --> 00:41:30.820
So therefore, 3 divides that,
which means 3 divides this.

00:41:30.820 --> 00:41:36.590
So that means 3 divides n
plus 1 cubed minus n plus 1.

00:41:36.590 --> 00:41:42.560
And we are done with
the proof by induction.

00:41:42.560 --> 00:41:43.768
Any questions about that one?

00:41:47.680 --> 00:41:50.600
So the key steps in induction
are always the same.

00:41:50.600 --> 00:41:53.490
You write down
"proof by induction."

00:41:53.490 --> 00:41:55.570
You identify your predicate.

00:41:55.570 --> 00:41:58.610
You do the base case,
usually n equals 0,

00:41:58.610 --> 00:42:00.140
but it could be something else.

00:42:00.140 --> 00:42:03.850
And then you do
your inductive step.

00:42:03.850 --> 00:42:06.115
Now in general, you could
start your induction--

00:42:06.115 --> 00:42:08.240
you don't have to start it
at 0, you could start it

00:42:08.240 --> 00:42:11.336
at some value b, some integer b.

00:42:16.610 --> 00:42:17.810
Let's take a look at that.

00:42:25.050 --> 00:42:29.900
So you could have
for the base case,

00:42:29.900 --> 00:42:35.130
you could have p of b
is true, not p of 0.

00:42:35.130 --> 00:42:40.730
And then for your
induction step you

00:42:40.730 --> 00:42:47.440
would have for all n bigger
than or equal to b, pn implies

00:42:47.440 --> 00:42:50.000
pn plus 1.

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:57.040
And then your conclusion is
that for all n bigger than

00:42:57.040 --> 00:43:00.790
or equal to b, pn is true.

00:43:00.790 --> 00:43:03.630
So inductions don't
always have to start at 0.

00:43:03.630 --> 00:43:05.790
You can pick where you start.

00:43:05.790 --> 00:43:10.150
Just make sure that you
verify the starting point

00:43:10.150 --> 00:43:12.940
and you verify the
implication for all n

00:43:12.940 --> 00:43:14.772
at that starting
point and beyond.

00:43:20.680 --> 00:43:25.950
All right, let's now do a
false proof using induction.

00:43:35.090 --> 00:43:42.130
We're going to prove that all
horses are the same color.

00:43:54.600 --> 00:43:57.270
So let's go through the process.

00:43:57.270 --> 00:44:04.750
So the proof, we write
down "by induction."

00:44:04.750 --> 00:44:08.320
Now we need our induction
hypothesis, the predicate.

00:44:08.320 --> 00:44:12.550
So we're going to let that
be-- we can't let it be this.

00:44:12.550 --> 00:44:14.950
Why can't this be our predicate?

00:44:14.950 --> 00:44:16.340
All horses are the same color.

00:44:16.340 --> 00:44:18.756
What's wrong with making that
be the induction hypothesis?

00:44:20.917 --> 00:44:22.250
You can't plug anything into it.

00:44:22.250 --> 00:44:23.900
There's no number here.

00:44:23.900 --> 00:44:27.050
I've got to have a
number, n, to induct on.

00:44:27.050 --> 00:44:37.000
So what I'm going to say is
that in any set of n horses--

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:42.180
and let's make n bigger
than or equal to 1--

00:44:42.180 --> 00:44:48.920
the horses are all
the same color.

00:44:55.600 --> 00:44:58.610
All right, now if I prove
this is true for all n,

00:44:58.610 --> 00:45:00.280
well then all horses
are the same color.

00:45:00.280 --> 00:45:02.738
Because in any set of n horses,
they're all the same color.

00:45:02.738 --> 00:45:05.860
So all horses must
be the same color.

00:45:05.860 --> 00:45:07.020
What's the next thing I do?

00:45:07.020 --> 00:45:09.150
What's the next step?

00:45:09.150 --> 00:45:11.870
Base case.

00:45:11.870 --> 00:45:16.790
Now, what am I going to
use as my base case here?

00:45:16.790 --> 00:45:21.580
One horse, OK, or n equals 1.

00:45:21.580 --> 00:45:22.920
So p of 1.

00:45:22.920 --> 00:45:26.650
That would say that any set
of one horses the horses

00:45:26.650 --> 00:45:28.510
are all the same color.

00:45:28.510 --> 00:45:29.050
That's true.

00:45:29.050 --> 00:45:29.841
I've got one horse.

00:45:29.841 --> 00:45:32.180
It's the same color as itself.

00:45:32.180 --> 00:45:33.970
So that's easy.

00:45:33.970 --> 00:45:38.310
It's true since just one horse.

00:46:03.240 --> 00:46:08.100
All right, what's the
next step of the proof?

00:46:08.100 --> 00:46:10.200
What's the next thing I do?

00:46:10.200 --> 00:46:11.180
Inductive step.

00:46:15.440 --> 00:46:28.060
So I'm going to assume that pn
is true to prove pn-- and show

00:46:28.060 --> 00:46:32.030
pn plus 1 is true.

00:46:32.030 --> 00:46:34.630
All right, so I'm
going to assume

00:46:34.630 --> 00:46:36.310
that in any set of
n horses, the horses

00:46:36.310 --> 00:46:38.680
are all the same color
that I start with.

00:46:38.680 --> 00:46:41.050
And now I look at a
set of n plus 1 horses.

00:46:44.160 --> 00:46:50.500
So we consider a set
of n plus 1 horses.

00:46:53.290 --> 00:47:00.060
And let's call those
horses h1, h2, hn plus 1.

00:47:03.820 --> 00:47:08.400
What do I know about
horses h1 to hn?

00:47:13.740 --> 00:47:17.340
They're the same color,
because pn is true.

00:47:17.340 --> 00:47:19.290
There are a set of n horses.

00:47:19.290 --> 00:47:21.140
By p1 they're all
the same color.

00:47:31.810 --> 00:47:42.221
Also, what do I know but
h2, h3 and hn plus 1?

00:47:42.221 --> 00:47:44.470
All the same color, because
they're a set of n horses.

00:47:48.430 --> 00:47:51.170
All right.

00:47:51.170 --> 00:48:01.760
Well, since the
color of h1 equals

00:48:01.760 --> 00:48:09.430
the color of those
guys, h2 to hn,

00:48:09.430 --> 00:48:12.560
I know h1 is the same
color as these guys.

00:48:12.560 --> 00:48:15.620
I also know that hn plus 1 is
the same color as those guys.

00:48:22.990 --> 00:48:27.440
That means that h1 is the
same color as hn plus 1.

00:48:27.440 --> 00:48:29.260
And all n plus 1
are the same color.

00:48:38.410 --> 00:48:39.700
And that's pn plus 1.

00:48:42.460 --> 00:48:45.660
That implies pn plus 1.

00:48:45.660 --> 00:48:46.460
And I'm done.

00:48:49.820 --> 00:48:54.720
Now a few years ago we assigned
this problem as homework.

00:48:54.720 --> 00:48:56.410
And we asked students
to figure out what

00:48:56.410 --> 00:48:57.860
went wrong with the problem.

00:48:57.860 --> 00:48:59.740
Why doesn't this work?

00:48:59.740 --> 00:49:03.230
And the responses were
a little discouraging.

00:49:03.230 --> 00:49:06.950
Half the class responded,
effectively as follows,

00:49:06.950 --> 00:49:09.980
this example just goes to show
that induction doesn't always

00:49:09.980 --> 00:49:12.560
work.

00:49:12.560 --> 00:49:15.430
A third of the
class said, I always

00:49:15.430 --> 00:49:17.390
knew that you can't
trust mathematics.

00:49:17.390 --> 00:49:21.140
This example just proves it.

00:49:21.140 --> 00:49:23.540
That really hurt.

00:49:23.540 --> 00:49:26.930
And most of the rest were
something similar to that.

00:49:26.930 --> 00:49:29.180
Not exactly what we were
looking for in the homework.

00:49:29.180 --> 00:49:31.030
So now we don't
leave it to homework.

00:49:31.030 --> 00:49:34.110
We do it in class.

00:49:34.110 --> 00:49:37.150
What's the flaw here?

00:49:37.150 --> 00:49:38.248
What was it?

00:49:38.248 --> 00:49:39.060
AUDIENCE: P of n.

00:49:39.060 --> 00:49:39.810
PROFESSOR: P of n?

00:49:39.810 --> 00:49:40.873
What's wrong with p of n?

00:49:40.873 --> 00:49:41.748
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:49:45.690 --> 00:49:47.380
PROFESSOR: No, this
is a real assumption

00:49:47.380 --> 00:49:52.280
in any set of n horses--
depends on n-- the horses are

00:49:52.280 --> 00:49:53.150
all the same color.

00:49:53.150 --> 00:49:55.730
That is a proposition.

00:49:55.730 --> 00:49:58.340
Because it depends on
n, it's a predicate.

00:49:58.340 --> 00:50:00.990
It's true or it's false.

00:50:00.990 --> 00:50:04.840
Now we know it's false, because
you could get a set of a couple

00:50:04.840 --> 00:50:06.670
horses with different color.

00:50:06.670 --> 00:50:07.740
But it is a proposition.

00:50:07.740 --> 00:50:10.640
Yeah, way back there?

00:50:10.640 --> 00:50:13.840
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] for
like a certain set of horses.

00:50:13.840 --> 00:50:15.940
So even though it's the
same number of horses,

00:50:15.940 --> 00:50:20.638
so it was the same number
as a different set of horses

00:50:20.638 --> 00:50:23.077
it's not something you
can assume anymore.

00:50:23.077 --> 00:50:24.410
PROFESSOR: That's a great point.

00:50:24.410 --> 00:50:28.450
I did gloss over something
here, because in the predicate

00:50:28.450 --> 00:50:30.860
I've got "in any set."

00:50:30.860 --> 00:50:34.724
So there's really a "for
all sets" sitting out here.

00:50:34.724 --> 00:50:36.140
So I've going to
be careful that I

00:50:36.140 --> 00:50:41.080
establish that when I'm trying
to prove pn implies pn plus 1.

00:50:41.080 --> 00:50:43.520
So to establish
pn plus 1 here, I

00:50:43.520 --> 00:50:45.710
assume pn which means
in any set of n horses

00:50:45.710 --> 00:50:46.860
they're all the same color.

00:50:46.860 --> 00:50:47.910
That I'm given.

00:50:47.910 --> 00:50:48.840
That's pn.

00:50:48.840 --> 00:50:52.500
I've got to look at any
set of n plus 1 horses.

00:50:52.500 --> 00:50:58.270
So consider any set, not a set,
any set of n plus 1 horses.

00:50:58.270 --> 00:51:00.060
So you pick any set you want.

00:51:00.060 --> 00:51:03.870
Call them this, h1
through hn plus 1.

00:51:03.870 --> 00:51:08.900
Well then, the first n are a set
of n horses, so I can apply pn,

00:51:08.900 --> 00:51:11.290
therefore they have
the same color.

00:51:11.290 --> 00:51:14.860
The last n horses in the
set are a set of n horses,

00:51:14.860 --> 00:51:16.590
so I can imply pn.

00:51:16.590 --> 00:51:19.750
So these guys all have the same
color, and I'm on my merry way

00:51:19.750 --> 00:51:20.810
here.

00:51:20.810 --> 00:51:23.800
So you're right, I had to
do a little bit more work,

00:51:23.800 --> 00:51:26.660
but I can do that work
and I still get a proof.

00:51:26.660 --> 00:51:28.114
Yeah?

00:51:28.114 --> 00:51:28.989
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:51:28.989 --> 00:51:30.030
PROFESSOR: Good question.

00:51:30.030 --> 00:51:31.950
Is there a problem
with the base case?

00:51:31.950 --> 00:51:37.270
So my base case was
here, n equals 1.

00:51:37.270 --> 00:51:42.060
In any set of one horse, the
horses-- let's say in the set

00:51:42.060 --> 00:51:47.960
just to be really careful--
are all the same color.

00:51:47.960 --> 00:51:51.100
No, in any set of one horses
there's only one horse,

00:51:51.100 --> 00:51:53.080
so it's the same
color as itself.

00:51:53.080 --> 00:51:54.096
Yeah?

00:51:54.096 --> 00:51:54.971
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:51:57.780 --> 00:52:00.622
PROFESSOR: n plus 1 is
not the same as n, yeah.

00:52:00.622 --> 00:52:02.088
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:02.088 --> 00:52:04.896
So you can't have
the same assumption

00:52:04.896 --> 00:52:06.768
because it's not
a set of n horses.

00:52:06.768 --> 00:52:08.395
It's a set of n plus 1?

00:52:08.395 --> 00:52:09.520
PROFESSOR: Well, let's see.

00:52:09.520 --> 00:52:12.700
So you're arguing I made
a mistake here, right?

00:52:12.700 --> 00:52:16.230
Well, I've got horses--
horse 2, 3, up to n plus 1.

00:52:16.230 --> 00:52:18.000
How many horses are
in this set here?

00:52:20.640 --> 00:52:21.802
AUDIENCE: Oh, in that set?

00:52:21.802 --> 00:52:22.760
PROFESSOR: In this set.

00:52:22.760 --> 00:52:24.400
How many horses are there?

00:52:24.400 --> 00:52:24.900
AUDIENCE: N.

00:52:24.900 --> 00:52:28.270
PROFESSOR: N. So I can apply p
of n to this set just the same

00:52:28.270 --> 00:52:31.290
as that set, because p of
n is any set of n horses.

00:52:31.290 --> 00:52:35.097
Well, I'm picking this one
now and applying pn to it.

00:52:35.097 --> 00:52:36.930
And so therefore they're
all the same color.

00:52:39.760 --> 00:52:41.646
Yeah?

00:52:41.646 --> 00:52:44.060
AUDIENCE: H1, h2, dot, dot, dot.

00:52:44.060 --> 00:52:45.450
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:52:45.450 --> 00:52:48.414
AUDIENCE: Because it does
work it there's two or more,

00:52:48.414 --> 00:52:52.370
but you didn't prove it with
just one-- or from one to two.

00:52:52.370 --> 00:52:53.175
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:52:53.175 --> 00:52:54.758
Remember I told you
that dot, dot, dot

00:52:54.758 --> 00:52:57.740
is so reasonable,
so easy to use.

00:52:57.740 --> 00:52:58.540
Everybody uses it.

00:52:58.540 --> 00:53:00.440
It was going to catch us up.

00:53:00.440 --> 00:53:02.420
The bug is in the dot, dot, dot.

00:53:02.420 --> 00:53:08.775
And in particular, it has to
do with the case n equal 2.

00:53:08.775 --> 00:53:10.400
So there's two ways
to look at the bug,

00:53:10.400 --> 00:53:13.580
dot, dot, dot, or
we didn't completely

00:53:13.580 --> 00:53:16.090
do all the inductive steps.

00:53:16.090 --> 00:53:19.680
So let's look at the case--
actually it's the case n

00:53:19.680 --> 00:53:25.090
equals 1, here, in
this inductive step.

00:53:25.090 --> 00:53:30.780
Did I prove p1 implies p2?

00:53:30.780 --> 00:53:33.160
Let's just double check
that worked for n equals 1.

00:53:40.630 --> 00:53:42.066
n equals 1.

00:53:42.066 --> 00:53:46.030
I've got a set of two horses.

00:53:46.030 --> 00:53:48.360
This becomes 2.

00:53:48.360 --> 00:53:51.542
So I've got h1, h2.

00:53:51.542 --> 00:53:52.750
Nothing in the dot, dot, dot.

00:53:52.750 --> 00:53:55.310
It's just h1 and h2.

00:53:55.310 --> 00:54:01.570
Then this becomes h1.

00:54:01.570 --> 00:54:04.260
So sure enough, h1 is
the same color as itself.

00:54:04.260 --> 00:54:07.170
This becomes-- what does this
become, this set of horses?

00:54:07.170 --> 00:54:08.990
What is it really?

00:54:08.990 --> 00:54:11.590
h2.

00:54:11.590 --> 00:54:13.190
All right, so I've
got the color of h1

00:54:13.190 --> 00:54:16.550
equals the color
of-- oh man, this

00:54:16.550 --> 00:54:18.850
is so hard to see this bug.

00:54:18.850 --> 00:54:23.550
I wrote down h2 dot, dot,
dot, to hn because-- take out

00:54:23.550 --> 00:54:26.410
h1, what's left?

00:54:26.410 --> 00:54:28.550
What's left is h2 through hn.

00:54:28.550 --> 00:54:29.830
But this set is only h1.

00:54:29.830 --> 00:54:30.830
What's really left here?

00:54:30.830 --> 00:54:31.600
What is this set?

00:54:34.400 --> 00:54:35.190
What is this set?

00:54:39.980 --> 00:54:41.962
h2, h1?

00:54:41.962 --> 00:54:43.450
No.

00:54:43.450 --> 00:54:45.870
You see, what is the whole
set? h1, dot, dot, dot, hn.

00:54:45.870 --> 00:54:46.870
What is the whole thing?

00:54:46.870 --> 00:54:48.930
It's just h1.

00:54:48.930 --> 00:54:52.950
pull out h1 and look
at the rest of it,

00:54:52.950 --> 00:54:55.600
how many horses are here?

00:54:55.600 --> 00:54:56.580
0 horses.

00:54:59.240 --> 00:55:01.120
This is the empty set.

00:55:01.120 --> 00:55:04.560
There are no horses
here to compare to.

00:55:04.560 --> 00:55:08.220
Even though I got an h2, I got
an hn, I got a dot, dot, dot.

00:55:08.220 --> 00:55:11.770
Because generally,
if n is big, this

00:55:11.770 --> 00:55:13.870
has n minus 1 horses are here.

00:55:13.870 --> 00:55:15.310
There's n total.

00:55:15.310 --> 00:55:18.120
I got n minus 1 right here.

00:55:18.120 --> 00:55:20.280
But n minus 1 is 0.

00:55:20.280 --> 00:55:22.680
There are no horses here.

00:55:22.680 --> 00:55:27.220
And so this bridge in the
equality totally breaks.

00:55:27.220 --> 00:55:31.910
I got color of h1 equals--
there's no information here--

00:55:31.910 --> 00:55:33.882
equals the color of h2.

00:55:33.882 --> 00:55:35.590
There's no equality
here, because there's

00:55:35.590 --> 00:55:39.380
no horses in this set, all
because of that dot, dot, dot.

00:55:39.380 --> 00:55:43.360
Do you see where the problem
is by using the dot, dot, dot?

00:55:43.360 --> 00:55:46.912
For the case n equals-- it was
true for every other case of n.

00:55:46.912 --> 00:55:51.240
n equals 2, n equals
3, it's all true.

00:55:51.240 --> 00:55:55.360
In fact, what we proved, we
proved the base case of p1

00:55:55.360 --> 00:55:57.030
is true.

00:55:57.030 --> 00:55:59.610
This is an argument
that p2 implies p3.

00:55:59.610 --> 00:56:01.790
That is true.

00:56:01.790 --> 00:56:06.680
p3 implies p4, that is true.

00:56:06.680 --> 00:56:08.200
And so forth.

00:56:08.200 --> 00:56:11.050
We proved for all n
bigger than or equal to 2,

00:56:11.050 --> 00:56:13.780
pn implies pn plus 1.

00:56:13.780 --> 00:56:15.440
That we proved.

00:56:15.440 --> 00:56:20.060
What is the one missing
implication we did not prove?

00:56:20.060 --> 00:56:24.410
The missing link, p1 implies p2.

00:56:24.410 --> 00:56:26.080
We did not prove that.

00:56:26.080 --> 00:56:28.650
Now is that true?

00:56:28.650 --> 00:56:30.350
No.

00:56:30.350 --> 00:56:33.330
You can find a set of two
horses are not the same color.

00:56:33.330 --> 00:56:35.880
And just because every horse
is the same color as itself,

00:56:35.880 --> 00:56:37.400
does not give you that.

00:56:37.400 --> 00:56:39.432
That was missing in this proof.

00:56:39.432 --> 00:56:40.890
And so we have to
be really careful

00:56:40.890 --> 00:56:43.510
when you're doing these
proofs that you establish

00:56:43.510 --> 00:56:45.620
the inductive step
for all n bigger

00:56:45.620 --> 00:56:47.032
than or equal to the base case.

00:56:47.032 --> 00:56:48.490
And then make sure,
if you're going

00:56:48.490 --> 00:56:51.790
to use this really convenient
dot dot dot notation, that you

00:56:51.790 --> 00:56:55.650
don't wind up here saying, oh
this is horses h2 through hn

00:56:55.650 --> 00:57:00.640
when there's no horses
there, because n is 1.

00:57:00.640 --> 00:57:02.370
Any questions about this?

00:57:02.370 --> 00:57:03.302
Yeah?

00:57:03.302 --> 00:57:04.177
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:57:08.580 --> 00:57:09.670
PROFESSOR: Great question.

00:57:09.670 --> 00:57:11.970
All right, let's fix the proof.

00:57:11.970 --> 00:57:14.500
Start with the base
case of p of 2,

00:57:14.500 --> 00:57:16.250
and now I've got all this done.

00:57:16.250 --> 00:57:19.665
So therefore, that's
another proof.

00:57:19.665 --> 00:57:20.165
Yeah?

00:57:23.530 --> 00:57:24.357
Say it again.

00:57:24.357 --> 00:57:25.232
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:57:28.834 --> 00:57:30.250
PROFESSOR: This
is still the same.

00:57:30.250 --> 00:57:34.515
In any set of n bigger than
or equal to two horses,

00:57:34.515 --> 00:57:36.390
all the horses in the
set are the same color.

00:57:36.390 --> 00:57:37.390
That's what he saying.

00:57:37.390 --> 00:57:40.000
And he's saying, hey look,
the proof worked here.

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:41.930
The inductive step is just fine.

00:57:41.930 --> 00:57:44.630
p2 does imply p3.

00:57:44.630 --> 00:57:45.512
Yeah?

00:57:45.512 --> 00:57:47.220
AUDIENCE: The base
case for 2 isn't true.

00:57:47.220 --> 00:57:48.219
PROFESSOR: That's right.

00:57:48.219 --> 00:57:51.060
The base case fails.

00:57:51.060 --> 00:57:54.450
That's why you've always
got to check the base case.

00:57:54.450 --> 00:57:55.390
Yeah?

00:57:55.390 --> 00:57:59.851
AUDIENCE: What it does prove is
that if you find any two horse

00:57:59.851 --> 00:58:02.725
and they're always going
to be the same color,

00:58:02.725 --> 00:58:04.650
then all horses have
to be the same color.

00:58:04.650 --> 00:58:05.770
PROFESSOR: That's correct.

00:58:05.770 --> 00:58:07.170
That's a great point.

00:58:07.170 --> 00:58:10.580
We have given a proof that if
you look at any pair of horses

00:58:10.580 --> 00:58:14.380
and they're the same color, then
all horses are the same color.

00:58:14.380 --> 00:58:16.620
That's true.

00:58:16.620 --> 00:58:17.790
That is true.

00:58:17.790 --> 00:58:19.370
Of course, there
are pairs of horses

00:58:19.370 --> 00:58:21.000
that aren't the same color.

00:58:21.000 --> 00:58:22.560
So the base case would fail.

00:58:22.560 --> 00:58:24.170
So always check the base case.

00:58:24.170 --> 00:58:25.860
You could prove some
great stuff if you

00:58:25.860 --> 00:58:26.950
don't check the base case.

00:58:30.670 --> 00:58:34.262
All right, any other
questions about that?

00:58:34.262 --> 00:58:37.148
Yeah?

00:58:37.148 --> 00:58:39.994
AUDIENCE: Negative
number [INAUDIBLE]?

00:58:39.994 --> 00:58:40.660
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:58:40.660 --> 00:58:41.806
As long as it's an integer.

00:58:41.806 --> 00:58:43.790
And as long as you
prove pn implies

00:58:43.790 --> 00:58:46.390
pn plus 1 starting
there all the way out.

00:58:46.390 --> 00:58:48.990
Yeah, you can start at
negative numbers if you want.

00:58:48.990 --> 00:58:51.500
Usually there's not many
cases where that comes up

00:58:51.500 --> 00:58:52.630
you want to, but you can.

00:58:52.630 --> 00:58:55.030
Nothing wrong with that.

00:58:55.030 --> 00:58:57.730
Any other questions?

00:58:57.730 --> 00:59:02.820
Yeah, you can see why it was
a messy homework problem.

00:59:02.820 --> 00:59:04.790
So far we've seen
examples of how induction

00:59:04.790 --> 00:59:09.220
is useful in proving the
hypothesis is true, but not

00:59:09.220 --> 00:59:12.920
in solving the problem, per se.

00:59:12.920 --> 00:59:16.540
Or even figuring out what
the hypothesis should be.

00:59:16.540 --> 00:59:19.400
Now in the last
example, we're going

00:59:19.400 --> 00:59:21.330
to show you how
induction can be used

00:59:21.330 --> 00:59:24.300
to prove there is a
solution to a problem,

00:59:24.300 --> 00:59:25.727
and also how to
find the solution.

00:59:25.727 --> 00:59:28.310
So it's actually going to be a
very useful, constructive thing

00:59:28.310 --> 00:59:29.390
in this case.

00:59:29.390 --> 00:59:31.390
Now this problem arose
in the construction

00:59:31.390 --> 00:59:35.110
of the status center, the
building we're in now.

00:59:35.110 --> 00:59:37.950
This whole building was
originally supposed to cost,

00:59:37.950 --> 00:59:41.120
completely furnished,
under $100 million.

00:59:41.120 --> 00:59:42.400
That was the goal.

00:59:42.400 --> 00:59:45.000
But the first mistake they
made was the first step,

00:59:45.000 --> 00:59:46.260
was hiring the architect.

00:59:46.260 --> 00:59:47.820
They hired Frank Gehry.

00:59:47.820 --> 00:59:51.350
I think MIT is now in a
lawsuit with Frank Gehry.

00:59:51.350 --> 00:59:53.200
So he was the architect.

00:59:53.200 --> 00:59:55.600
And costs just went nuts.

00:59:55.600 --> 00:59:57.960
As you could imagine,
all these slanted walls

00:59:57.960 --> 01:00:00.850
and crazy things happening
actually are expensive.

01:00:00.850 --> 01:00:05.862
And the cost quickly got
over $300 million, literally.

01:00:05.862 --> 01:00:06.820
That that's parts true.

01:00:06.820 --> 01:00:10.180
Now I'm going to
fabricate a little bit.

01:00:10.180 --> 01:00:13.562
Now actually, fund raising
became a huge priority

01:00:13.562 --> 01:00:15.020
once they're more
than $200 million

01:00:15.020 --> 01:00:17.670
over budget they haven't even
bought the furniture yet.

01:00:17.670 --> 01:00:21.000
So some pretty radical
ideas were proposed.

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:24.390
And one of them was to build
a large 2 to the n by 2

01:00:24.390 --> 01:00:27.080
to the n courtyard
and put a statue

01:00:27.080 --> 01:00:31.990
of a wealthy, potential donor
in the center of the courtyard.

01:00:31.990 --> 01:00:35.390
So let's draw this.

01:00:47.370 --> 01:00:50.780
So the courtyard--
and of course,

01:00:50.780 --> 01:00:55.380
you know, it's computer science,
so it has to be a power of 2.

01:00:55.380 --> 01:00:59.760
So it's 2 to the
n by 2 to the n.

01:00:59.760 --> 01:01:04.060
And I've drawn here
the case n equals 2.

01:01:04.060 --> 01:01:07.960
And we've got to get the
statue of the wealthy guy

01:01:07.960 --> 01:01:08.614
in the middle.

01:01:08.614 --> 01:01:10.280
And I'm not supposed
to reveal his name.

01:01:10.280 --> 01:01:11.970
So we're just going
to call him Bill.

01:01:15.980 --> 01:01:18.130
So Bill's got to
go in the center.

01:01:18.130 --> 01:01:20.920
Now this would be fine,
except to that nothing

01:01:20.920 --> 01:01:22.870
was easy with Frank
Gehry, everything

01:01:22.870 --> 01:01:25.310
was some weird,
weird thing going on.

01:01:25.310 --> 01:01:28.860
And he insisted on
using l-shaped tiles

01:01:28.860 --> 01:01:30.660
for the courtyard.

01:01:30.660 --> 01:01:34.560
So the tiles that we're going
to use looked like this.

01:01:34.560 --> 01:01:38.260
So it's almost a two
by two, except you're

01:01:38.260 --> 01:01:41.220
missing that piece.

01:01:41.220 --> 01:01:42.930
So what you need to
figure out how to do

01:01:42.930 --> 01:01:47.000
is tie all this courtyard
perfectly leaving

01:01:47.000 --> 01:01:50.060
one spot for Bill
using tiles like this,

01:01:50.060 --> 01:01:51.125
these l-shaped tiles.

01:01:57.400 --> 01:01:58.650
And this is 2 by 2 here.

01:02:01.460 --> 01:02:03.150
So that's the task.

01:02:03.150 --> 01:02:07.030
So let's see if we can do
that for n equals 2 here.

01:02:11.090 --> 01:02:15.040
Let's see, we can
do a tile here.

01:02:15.040 --> 01:02:19.100
We can do a tile here.

01:02:19.100 --> 01:02:20.870
A tile here.

01:02:20.870 --> 01:02:22.520
A tile here.

01:02:22.520 --> 01:02:24.730
And a tile there.

01:02:24.730 --> 01:02:25.320
So we can.

01:02:25.320 --> 01:02:28.530
In this case we can tile
the courtyard perfectly

01:02:28.530 --> 01:02:32.440
using these L shaped
tiles, leaving one square

01:02:32.440 --> 01:02:36.819
in the Center for the statue.

01:02:36.819 --> 01:02:39.110
All right, everyone understand
what we're trying to do?

01:02:39.110 --> 01:02:40.790
The goal?

01:02:40.790 --> 01:02:42.398
Now I want to do it for n.

01:02:46.070 --> 01:02:50.999
So let's start proving
it by induction,

01:02:50.999 --> 01:02:52.790
even though we don't
know how to do it yet.

01:02:52.790 --> 01:02:55.123
Because we're going to see
how induction's going to help

01:02:55.123 --> 01:02:58.745
us show it's possible and maybe
even show us how to do it.

01:03:03.594 --> 01:03:04.635
So let's state a theorem.

01:03:07.970 --> 01:03:18.470
For all n there exists away
to tile a 2 to the n by 2

01:03:18.470 --> 01:03:28.840
to the n region, or courtyard,
with a center square missing

01:03:28.840 --> 01:03:29.480
for Bill.

01:03:43.222 --> 01:03:44.680
And the proof will
